 and political dynamics through which the demands of organized labor and the imperatives of capitalist growth have evolved from a period of open conflict and stagnation to one of class compromise. He also demonstrates that the Kerala model has broad ramifications for understanding the relationship between substantive democracy and market economies in low-income countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aLabor movementzIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aLabor unionszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aPeasantszIndiazKeralaxHistory. 0aWorking classzIndiazKeralaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aSocial Work.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172073440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501720734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501720734/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles